<doc id="73390" wikidata="Q830513" url="?curid=73390" title="Residue theorem">
<text>In complex analysis, the residue theorem, sometimes called Cauchy&#x27;s residue theorem, is a powerful tool to evaluate line integrals of analytic functions over closed curves; it can often be used to compute real integrals and infinite series as well. It generalizes the Cauchy integral theorem and Cauchy&#x27;s integral formula. The residue theorem should not be confused with special cases of the generalized Stokes&#x27; theorem; however, the latter can be used as an ingredient of its proof.

==Statement of Cauchy&#x27;s residue theorem==

The statement is as follows:

Residue theorem: Let formula_1 be a simply connected open subset of the complex plane containing a finite list of points formula_2 formula_3 and a function formula_4 holomorphic on formula_5 Letting formula_6 be a closed rectifiable curve in formula_7 and denoting the residue of formula_4 at each point formula_9 by formula_10 and the winding number of formula_6 around formula_9 by formula_13 the line integral of formula_4 around formula_6 is equal to formula_16 times the sum of residues, each counted as many times as formula_6 winds around the respective point:

formula_18

If formula_6 is a positively oriented simple closed curve, formula_20 is formula_21 if formula_9 is in the interior of formula_6 and formula_24 if not, therefore

formula_25

with the sum over those formula_9 inside 
The relationship of the residue theorem to Stokes&#x27; theorem is given by the Jordan curve theorem. The general plane curve must first be reduced to a set of simple closed curves formula_27 whose total is equivalent to formula_6 for integration purposes; this reduces the problem to finding the integral of formula_29 along a Jordan curve formula_30 with interior formula_31 The requirement that formula_4 be holomorphic on formula_33 is equivalent to the statement that the exterior derivative formula_34 on formula_5 Thus if two planar regions formula_36 and formula_37 of formula_1 enclose the same subset formula_39 of formula_40 the regions formula_41 and formula_42 lie entirely in formula_7 hence

formula_44

is well-defined and equal to zero. Consequently, the contour integral of formula_29 along formula_46 is equal to the sum of a set of integrals along paths formula_47 each enclosing an arbitrarily small region around a single formula_48 — the residues of formula_4 (up to the conventional factor formula_16 at formula_51 Summing over formula_52 we recover the final expression of the contour integral in terms of the winding numbers formula_53

In order to evaluate real integrals, the residue theorem is used in the following manner: the integrand is extended to the complex plane and its residues are computed (which is usually easy), and a part of the real axis is extended to a closed curve by attaching a half-circle in the upper or lower half-plane, forming a semicircle. The integral over this curve can then be computed using the residue theorem. Often, the half-circle part of the integral will tend towards zero as the radius of the half-circle grows, leaving only the real-axis part of the integral, the one we were originally interested in.

